<br>&nbsp;
<center><b><font face="Arial"><font color="#3366FF"><font size=+1>Microsoft
Project 2000 and Project Central</font></font></font></b></center>

<blockquote>To get up-to-date project information using Microsoft Project
Central, a Web-based companion to Microsoft project 2000 that can be installed
on company's Intranet or the Internet. Microsoft project Central allows
two-way communication between everyone involved in a project. It allows
team members to update the plan as they perform their tasks, and gives
everyone unprecedented visibility into the status of their project.</blockquote>

<blockquote><b><i><font face="Arial">Collaborative Planning with Microsoft
Project Central :</font></i></b></blockquote>

<ul>
<ul>
<li>
Personal Gantt Chart: to outline each team member’s own tasks across multiple
projects.<br>
<BR></li>

<li>
New Task : Team member can create new Tasks, but the project manager should
approve them before adding them to project plan.<br>
<BR></li>

<li>
Task Delegation: Once assigned by the project manager, tasks may be deleted
from leads to team members or from peer to peer. Delegation can be disabled.<br>
<BR></li>
</ul>
<b><i><font face="Arial">Collaborative Tracking With Microsoft Project
Central :</font></i></b><br>
<BR>
<ul>
<li>
Timesheet: This is where team members can see their assignments across
projects, enter updates and easily send them to the project manager.<br>
<BR></li>

<li>
Administration Module: This provides project administrators with more control
over definitions of non-project time, views, formatting styles and security.<br>
<BR></li>

<li>
Offline Capabilities: Team members can take their timesheets and status
reports offline and continue working on them from wherever they are.</li>
</ul>
</ul>

